### Strings in Rust

Rust has two primary string types: `String` (heap-allocated, growable) and `&str` (string slice, borrowed reference).

---

### `String` vs `&str`

| Feature | `String` | `&str` |
|---------|----------|--------|
| Ownership | Owned | Borrowed reference |
| Mutable | Yes | No |
| Heap allocated | Yes | No (can be anywhere) |
| Growable | Yes | No |
| Creation | `String::from()`, `to_string()` | String literals are `&str` |

---

### Common Operations

```rust
// Creating strings
let s1 = String::from("hello");
let s2 = "world".to_string();
let s3 = &s1[0..2];  // slice: "he"

// Concatenation
let s4 = s1 + " " + &s2;  // s1 is moved!
let s5 = format!("{} {}", "hello", "world");

// Methods
println!("Length: {}", s5.len());
println!("Is empty: {}", s5.is_empty());
let contains = s5.contains("world");
```

> **Key Point:** Strings are UTF-8 encoded, so indexing by byte position is not always safe. Use string slices with caution, as they operate on bytes, not characters.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    let mut s = String::from("Hello");
    s.push_str(", ");
    s.push_str("Rust!");
    s.push('\n');

    let slice: &str = &s[0..5];
    println!("Slice: {}", slice);
    println!("Full: {}", s);
    println!("Length: {}", s.len());
}
